frameDefinitions: This frame describes a Sufferer who experiences the loss of someone through death.
This frame is concerned with the likelihood of a Hypothetical_event occurring.
This frame characterizes the likelihood that a Hypothetical_event will happen as a position on a scale of impossible to inevitable.
This frame contains adjectives and nouns that describe the truth or sincerity of communication.
This frame has to do with the bias or lack of bias of a Judge making an assessment concerning two or more Sides.
The lexical units in this frame are descriptions of a Cognizer's Attitude about or outlook on a State_of_affairs.     '' 'Carl is becoming more pessimistic about the negotiations every day.'
frameExamples: She <t>lost</t> her husband in the war.
It is <t>likely</t> that he'll arrive late.
Evelyn was <t>candid</t> with me about the party.
Carl is becoming more <t>pessimistic</t> about the negotiations every day.
listRoleDefinitions: The being or entity that emotionally experiences the death of the <fen>Deceased</fen>.
The entity that has died.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Deceased</fen> passed away.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Deceased</fen> passed away.
The state of affairs or occurrence whose likelihood is assessed.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
A numerical representation of the probability that a Hypothetical_event will occur.
A metaphorical representation of the position on the scale of likelihood that the Hypothetical_event will occur.
The event that is expected to happen with a certain likelihood.

The <fen>Speaker</fen> produces the <fen>Message</fen>, the truth or sincerity of which is at issue. It is normally expressed as the External Argument of predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word, or as the Nominal Head of prenominal uses.

<fen>Message</fen> is the communicative content whose truth or sincerity is at issue. This role does not normally co-occur with the other FEs in this frame. When it does occur, it is normally the External Argument of a predicative use of the <t>Target</t> word, or the modified Nominal Head in a prenominal use.

The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Message</fen> pertains. It often occurs without the <fen>Message</fen> role in predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word. It is normally expressed as a PP Complement headed by 'about'.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical or abstract setting in which the <fen>Message</fen> is conveyed.
This Frame Element marks the person whose objectivity in making assesment is being evaluated.
This Frame Element marks one of the <fen>Sides</fen> in a dispute or one of the alternatives in a situation of choice.
This Frame Element marks phrases jointly expressing both <fen>Sides</fen> in a dispute or all of the alternatives in a situation of choice.
The second-mentioned of the <fen>Sides</fen> to a dispute or alternatives in a situation of choice.
This Frame Element marks expressions that indicate how the bias of the <fen>Judge</fen> expresses itself in their behavior or actions.
The <fen>Dispute</fen> is the situation in which there is some conflict between two sides.
The individual whose point of view is taken in assigning the judgment denoted by the target.
The <fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part or action by a body part which indicates the character of the <fen>Decision_maker</fen>.
This role denotes the time when the partiality occurs.
The person whose <fen>Attitude</fen> about a <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> is being expressed.
The outlook or viewpoint expressed by the <fen>Cognizer</fen>.
An event, topic, or situation about which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> has an <fen>Attitude</fen>.
The Time interval during which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> has the <fen>Attitude</fen> about the <fen>State_of_affairs</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Rain</fex> is fairly unlikely today, I think.
There is a high chance of rain <fex>today</fex>.
There is a high chance of rain <fex>in Seattle</fex>.
There's a <fex>95 %</fex> chance of rain today.
Chances are <fex>slim</fex> that he'll pull through.
He's got a small chance <fex>of making it out alive</fex>.
<fex>Evelyn</fex> was candid about the party.
Evelyn made some candid <fex>remarks</fex>.
Evelyn was candid <fex>about the party</fex>.
Evelyn made some candid remarks <fex>in French</fex>.
<fex>The referee</fex> was totally biased against our team.
The umpire was partial <fex>to the home team</fex>.
The judge was neutral <fex>between the parties</fex>.
The judge favored the defendant <fex>over the plaintiff</fex>.
The judge made a biased <fex>decision</fex>.
My sister remained neutral <fex>in our disputes</fex>.
He had a neutral <fex>smile</fex> on his face.
<fex>Americans</fex> are optimistic despite the climbing unemployment rate.
Michelle had a somewhat negative <fex>outlook</fex> on the direction her life was heading.
<fex>The economy</fex> looks quite grim at this moment.
